<div id="review_3394556747" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3394556747" />
    <a title="sarah" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/57354360-sarah"><img alt="sarah" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1567765387p2/57354360.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3394556747?book_show_action=true">Jun 19, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="sarah" class="user" itemprop="url" name="sarah" href="/user/show/57354360-sarah">sarah</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 9780141182551" href="/book/show/425112.The_Crucible">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/57354360-sarah?shelf=on-my-shelf">on-my-shelf</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/57354360-sarah?shelf=read-2020">read-2020</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/57354360-sarah?shelf=my-reviews">my-reviews</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/57354360-sarah?shelf=classics">classics</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3394556747" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer11060826282952959622"><b>If you have somehow escaped reading this for school, here is a brief rundown:</b><br/><br/>The Crucible is set in 1692 Salem showing the danger of religious suppression, corruption and superstition. It tells the story of the hysteria and fear that grips the community after accusations of witchcraft surface and the subsequent witch trials, drawing parallels with the McCarthyism of the 1950s. The play focuses on themes of truth, reputation, loyalty and fear in an ultimately effective and engaging way. <br/><br/>This clas</span>
  <span id="freeText11060826282952959622" style="display:none"><b>If you have somehow escaped reading this for school, here is a brief rundown:</b><br /><br />The Crucible is set in 1692 Salem showing the danger of religious suppression, corruption and superstition. It tells the story of the hysteria and fear that grips the community after accusations of witchcraft surface and the subsequent witch trials, drawing parallels with the McCarthyism of the 1950s. The play focuses on themes of truth, reputation, loyalty and fear in an ultimately effective and engaging way. <br /><br />This classic is one that still holds value to modern audiences. There are many frightening parallels to draw to today's era, and it is important to learn about historical events in the hopes that it prevents them from repeating themselves. However, I do not think this is perfect and I definitely have some issues with how some characters are presented or changed from history. <br /><br /><b>I recently read this play for school so I really don’t feel like writing another essay on it, but here are a few thoughts: </b><br /><br />➽ Giles Corey &gt; John Proctor <br />➽ the line <i>“God is dead”</i> is iconic <br />➽ I would love to see this play in person<br />➽ the fact that this is history and not dystopian terrifies me <br />➽ Elizabeth proctor deserved better <br />➽ I love courtroom scenes and always will <br />➽ I will defend the separation of powers with my life <br />➽I would love to visit Salem one day (ahh.... imagine the day where we can travel again?)<br />➽ I felt a bit icky about the depiction of proctor as a misunderstood hero and Abigail as the literal devil. <br /><br />Overall, a quick and short read that both educates and entertains- I would recommend! <br />★★★☆☆.5 stars </span>
  <a data-text-id="11060826282952959622" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


